# Sample size calculation for testing one mean

* Recall in our body temperature example that the null $\mu_0=98.6$ and the observed mean was 98.25. 
* The _p_-value from the hypothesis test was highly significant.
* How big does the sample size $n$ need to be in order for the _p_-value to be _just barely_ significant?



Calculate $n$ when given $\alpha$, power ( $1-\beta$ ), "true" alternative mean $\mu$, and null $\mu_0$, _assuming_ the test statistic is normal (instead of t-distribution):

$$n=\left(s\frac{z_{1-\alpha/2}+z_{1-\beta}}{\mu-\mu_0}\right)^2$$




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
mu=98.25
mu0=98.6
sd=0.73
alpha=0.05
beta=0.20
n=(sd*(qnorm(1-alpha/2)+qnorm(1-beta))/(mu-mu0))^2
ceiling(n)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 35
```
:::
:::



_We would only need a sample size of 35!_ However, this is an under-estimate since we used the normal instead of t-distribution.

See http://powerandsamplesize.com/Calculators/Test-1-Mean/1-Sample-Equality.



## Power calculation for testing one mean

Conversely, we can calculate how much power we had in our example given the sample size of 130.

* Calculate power given $\alpha$, $n$, "true" alternative mean $\mu$, and null $\mu_0$, _assuming_ the test statistic is normal (instead of t-distribution)
    * where $\Phi$ is the probability for a standard normal distribution 

$$1-\beta=
		\Phi\left(z-z_{1-\alpha/2}\right)+\Phi\left(-z-z_{1-\alpha/2}\right)
		\quad ,\quad z=\frac{\mu-\mu_0}{s/\sqrt{n}}$$




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
mu=98.25; mu0=98.6; sd=0.73; alpha=0.05; n=130
z=(mu-mu0)/sd*sqrt(n)
Power=pnorm(z-qnorm(1-alpha/2))+
  pnorm(-z-qnorm(1-alpha/2))
Power
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 0.9997731
```
:::
:::




If the population mean is 98.2 instead of 98.6, we have a 99.98% chance of correctly rejecting $H_0$ when the sample size is 130.  
We would say this was over powered.



## Software for power and sample size calculations 



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
# sample size for one mean test
t.n <- power.t.test(  # base R power function
  delta = 98.6-98.25, sd=0.73,
    sig.level = 0.05, 
  power = 0.80, 
  type = "one.sample")
t.n
```

